Linux cgroups are used to limit resource consumption ( like CPU, Memory) 
by a process or processes on Linux.

Def:
Control groups, usually referred to as cgroups, are a Linux
kernel feature which allow processes to be organized into
hierarchical groups whose usage of various types of resources can then be limited and monitored.



Uses of cgroups:

Protect the system from a resource-hungry process
Ensure fair resource distribution among multiple applications
Test application performance under constrained resources
Guarantee resource availability in multi-tenant environments

How to added processes in cgroups:
1. Manipulating the virtual filesystem cgroupfs
2. Using libcgroup

Manipulating the virtual filesystem cgroupfs:

cgroupfs is a pseudo filesystem

On modern Linux distributions, this pseudo-filesystem is usually mounted at /sys/fs/cgroup

To create a new cgroup, just create a new subfolder under /sys/fs/cgroup

mkdir /sys/fs/cgroup/newcgroup

This newly created sub folder gets automatically populated with multiple files like given below:

cgroup.controllers      io.max
cgroup.events           io.stat
cgroup.freeze           memory.current
cgroup.max.depth        memory.events
cgroup.max.descendants  memory.events.local
cgroup.procs            memory.high
cgroup.stat             memory.low
cgroup.subtree_control  memory.max
cgroup.threads          memory.min
cgroup.type             memory.numa_stat
cpu.max                 memory.oom.group
cpu.stat                memory.stat


To limit CPU usage to 50%, run below command:
echo "50000 100000" > /sys/fs/cgroup/newcgroup/cpu.max

To limit memory to 100M, run below command:
echo "100M" > /sys/fs/cgroup/newcgroup/memory.max

Now, if we run a process, which we want to apply the just created limits, run below command:

PROC_PID=$(pgrep -xo <processname>)

echo ${PROC_PID} >> /sys/fs/cgroup/newcgroup/cgroup.procs

Now, this process , will be OOM killed if it exceeds the memory limit.


To move the current shell process to the cgroup, run below command:

echo $$ >> /sys/fs/cgroup/newcgroup/cgroup.procs


To remove the cgroup, run below command:

rmdir /sys/fs/cgroup/newcgroup

---
Using libcgroup:

Run below command to install necessary tools:
apt-get install cgroup-tools

To create new cgroup

cgcreate -g cpu,memory:/process_cg

To limit CPU and Memory

cgset -r cpu.max="50000 100000" process_cg

cgset -r memory.max="100M" process_cg


Now start the process ( for which limits need to be applied)

~/process

Now move it to the just created cgroup:

PROCESS_PID=$(pgrep -xo process)

cgclassify -g cpu,memory:process_cg ${PROCESS_PID}

NOTE: We can start the process in the desired cgroup, from the
beginning as
cgexec -g cpu,memory:process_cg ~/process


To delete the cgroup, run below command:
cgdelete -g cpu,memory:/process_cg

